	doi = {10.2337/dc06-0182},
	abstract = {OBJECTIVE: Diabetes is a significant risk factor for peripheral arterial disease (PAD) and is associated with accelerated atherosclerosis and limb loss. However, the pathophysiology involved in PAD is unclear. This study was conducted to evaluate the hemodynamic response to exercise of patients with and without diabetes and PAD.
RESEARCH DESIGN AND METHODS: The hemodynamic response in calf muscles of patients with diabetes, PAD, or both was determined using near-infrared spectroscopy (NIRS). Patients performed both a plantar-flexion and treadmill-walking exercise regimen.
